ce:section.ce:para:
The CQDs/CuCoFe-300 catalyst was prepared by a combination of calcination and liquid-phase synthesis methods. Firstly, CuCoFe-LDH was synthesized using a co-precipitation method and then calcined to form CuCoFe-300. Subsequently, the CQDs/CuCoFe-300 catalyst was prepared via the electrostatic interaction between the CuCoFe-300 surface with positive charges and the negatively charged of CQDs (as shown in Fig. 1

                        a). To better understand the physicochemical properties of CQDs/CuCoFe-300, it was necessary to first analyze the basic characteristics of CQDs. The particle size distribution histogram showed that the particle size of CQDs ranges from 2.4 to 6.4 nm, with an average size of 3.31 nm (
                           Fig. S1
                        ). Fluorescence and UV–visible spectra analyses indicated that CQDs exhibited the strongest broadband absorption around 336 nm (
                           Fig. S2
                        ). The CQDs aqueous solution appeared yellow–brown in sunlight and emitted bright blue fluorescence under UV light (
                           Fig. S3
                        ). All characterization results were consistent with the intrinsic physicochemical properties of CQDs reported, confirming the effective synthesis of CQDs [21,22]. Notably, previous studies had demonstrated the presence of abundant OVs on the surface of CuCoFe-300 [19].

It should be noted that despite the spatial distance being greater between the OVs on CuCoFe-300 and the C=O bonds in CQDs than with the surface hydroxyl groups, the strong electron-withdrawing characterization and sensitivity to oxygen atoms of OVs made them potential active sites for interaction with the C=O bonds in CQDs. Therefore, DFT calculations were employed to explore from a thermodynamic perspective whether the C=O bond in CQDs were more likely to interact directly with the hydroxyl groups on CuCoFe-300 or with the OV. The CQDs model was equivalent to C4 clusters simplistically in the calculation [18]. Under similar system energy, the DFT energy of C4 chain clusters (−3.05 eV) was significantly lower than that of C4 ring clusters (−1.48 eV), indicating a more stable structural characteristic overall (
                           Fig. S7
                        ). For this reason, selecting the chain-structured CQDs as the theoretical model was deemed more appropriate.
